ng\u003Eplantar calcaneonavicular ligament\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the spring ligament, plays a crucial role in supporting the head of the talus and maintaining the medial longitudinal arch of the foot. This ligament is essential for the structural integrity of the foot\u0027s arch, and its dysfunction can lead to flatfoot deformity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option \u003Cstrong\u003Econnects the calcaneus to the cuboid bone\u003C/strong\u003E describes the calcaneocuboid ligament, which is part of the lateral side of the foot and does not support the medial arch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option \u003Cstrong\u003Estabilises the lateral longitudinal arch\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the function of the long plantar ligament, which is involved in the lateral aspect of the foot\u0027s arch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevents excessive eversion of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E is more related to the function of the deltoid ligament, which is located on the medial side of the ankle and prevents excessive eversion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option \u003Cstrong\u003Econnects the navicular bone to the cuboid bone\u003C/strong\u003E describes the function of the cubonavicular ligament, which is not involved in supporting the medial longitudinal arch.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The plantar calcaneonavicular ligament, also known as the spring ligament, supports the head of the talus and maintains the medial longitudinal arch of the foot.","Damage to the plantar calcaneonavicular ligament can lead to flatfoot deformity due to loss of arch support."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University 